column168: SequenceEvent: A manage was unloading a trailer on door 78. The package slip out of his hand and broke when it hit the ground. I was called over to clean it up  when the manager realize liquid was coming out from the bottom. DescribePack: Part of the box got eaten away by the acid while I was making my way to unload 7. While I was cleaning up the package I found that only one glass bottle was broken. The other bottle was not damage nor was it leaking. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: I was wearing a apron and nitrile gloves while handling package. I used amphomag and absorbents to neutralized the spill. I put the glass bottles and box in one bag and placed the clean up in a another bag.

SequenceEvent: Plastic container of degreaser was damaged during either transit or unloading phase.  Leak was located at the the cap/seal on the top of container and was not noticed until being removed from IC belt by package handler at designated belt.  PH immediately notified me that there was a leaking hazmat.  Package was inspected and determined that there was a leak and needed to be processed as such. DescribePack: Metal seal/cap was cracked along seal which caused a small/slow leak from factory seal. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Upon inspection, leak was minor and located on the top of container.  Leaking hazmat was placed in a blue hazmat bag and then into a yellow hazmat drum

XPO Logistics terminal XCN experienced a UN2522 Visiomer Madame release from a 55-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 12-ounces of product released to a 2’ x 6” area of the metal drum lid/body. The release was due to the drum having the incorrect bung cap placed on it. The bung was replaced with a new one and secured for shipment on. The impacted drums were wiped down with absorbent pads which were then containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

SequenceEvent: When package was being unloaded from the trailer, it was wet so package was sent to QA for inspection by management. When inspected, two bottles inside package was found with loose caps causing leakage. DescribePack: Loose cap on plastic bottle was the cause of the leakage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was placed inside a plastic tote by management to contain the leakage.

SequenceEvent: Member of our management team went to our unloads where the leaking hazmat was discovered. DescribePack: The box was wet from the leaking contents, The label itself was starting to fade away due to the strong chemical inside. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Immediately placed the package inside of a lined tote and took it to our hood vent to help stop the horrible smell to stop spreading.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: On March 4, 2024, ten (10) one-gallon pails of paint related material were crushed in transit and released approximately seven (7) gallons of product to the truck interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Lone Star Hazmat (LSH) to remediate the impacted site. LSH utilized absorbents to recover the spilled product from the impacted trailer floor. All waste was collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums and staged onsite for future disposal. LSH repalletized the undamaged freight for continued shipping.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XDM experienced a UN3082 Mesotrione 40% SC release from a 135-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of product released to a 10’ x 15’ area of the concrete dock floor due to a puncture caused by other freight during dock operations. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one for shipment on. Absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted area. The damaged tote was cut up and containerized along with all impacted absorbents, pads, and PPE into (4) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

SequenceEvent: The package was found in the trailer laying sideways with the package orientation arrows facing sideways and the side of the box being wet. The hazmat package was put in a hazmat tote and brought to the QA cage for damage processing. DescribePack: The failure looks to have occurred with the cap on the bag which wound up leaking due to the package being loaded incorrectly into the trailer, which was from the package being laid on the side with the orientation arrows facing sideways instead of upwards. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: The hazmat package was put in a hazmat tote lined with a hazmat bag.

SequenceEvent: When the contents were discovered being coded for a refusal at the station for being damaged, we discovered that the contents (Which were 2 2.5-gallon jugs of liquid machine detergent which was a hazmat under UN 1760 Corrosive liquids N.O.S. Technical name Sodium Hydroxide) have leaked a small amount of the contents out of the package. Some of the box is wet due on the exterior but that is rain that has soaked a portion of the packaging. Upon closure inspection the caps were loose, and the corrosive liquids were observed to originate at the affected area. None of the liquid contents from inside of the package has been released out of the box, but still leaked from the inner jugs. No inner packing was found inside of the package. DescribePack: The Jugs were observed to have no leaks upon discovery, but some of the liquid inside of the container was out of the container and was at the time of discovery staining the inner exterior box. The caps enclosing the jugs containing the corrosive solution were observed to be loose with the most recently escaped liquid appearing right below the cap. The caps on the containers were promptly tightened and no leaks were observed after test and observing for a leak. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Upon awareness of the damaged hazmat, the caps were tightened prevent any further leaks.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE DISCOVERED ON VANLINE BELT, WET.  PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A HAZMAT BIN WITH A HAZMAT BAG LINER.  PIG MAT WAS USED TO ABSORB ANY EXCESS MOISTURE ON THE BELTLINE, THEN NEUTRALIZER WAS USED ON THE BELTLINE THAT STILL LOOKED MOIST.  UPON INSPECTION, PLASTIC CAP ON INNER GLASS JAR WAS FOUND TO BE CRACKED. DescribePack: UPON INSPECTION, BLUE PLASTIC CAP ON GLASS CONTAINER CRACKED ABOUT HALF WAY AROUND THE TOP EDGE OF CAP. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: AS SOON AS THE PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED TO BE WET, PACKAGE WAS REMOVED TO A HAZMAT BIN WITH A HAZMAT BAG LINER.

On March 5, 2024, one (!) 5-gallon pail of UN2922 was cracked during loading and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Mid-South Environmental Services (MSES) to remediate the impacted site. MSES personnel utilized hand tools, absorbents, and sodium bicarbonate to remediate the UN2922-impacted trailer floor. All impacted material was collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum and staged on site for transport and disposal.

SequenceEvent: We were called to trailer#822984 in the unload upon it being opened, for a presumed leaking hazmat. When we arrived, we found the hazmat loaded into the trailer upside down and above waist height, it was spilling all over the packages below it and spilled into the belly of the pup as well. All trk #'s above are pkgs that were damaged by this spill, they will be held until I get the disposition back for this incident. Hazmat spill protocol was followed, and all items are stored in Haz cage, spill was cleaned up and ph9'd cleanup supplies are in cage with damaged hazmat as well. Hazmat itself was placed in a hazardous materials tote lined with a bag and is on the corrosive pallet in the Haz cage. DescribePack: The pkg being upside down when loaded more than likely ruined the seal on the bucket. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Cleaned up and followed Haz spill protocol.

column168: On March 1, 2024, four (4) 5-gallon pails of paint were crushed in transit and released approximately ten (10) gallons of paint to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. TLE personnel utilized hand tools and absorbents to remediate the UN1263-impacted trailer. All impacted material was collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums and staged in the R+L heat room for transport and disposal.
